---
import Layout from "@layouts/Layout.astro";
import PageHero from "@components/marketing/PageHero.astro";
import ProseSection from "@components/marketing/ProseSection.astro";
import CardGrid from "@components/marketing/CardGrid.astro";
import CtaSection from "@components/marketing/CtaSection.astro";
import { comparePages } from "@config/navigation";

export const prerender = true;
const lang = "en";
---

<Layout
  title="Compare hydraulic modeling software"
  description="How epanet-js compares with Autodesk InfoWater Pro, Bentley OpenFlows WaterCAD and WaterGEMS, and Autodesk InfoWorks WS Pro: features, pricing, licensing, and how to use them together."
  lang={lang}>
  <PageHero
    align="center"
    title="How epanet-js compares"
    subtitle="Honest, side-by-side comparisons of epanet-js and the commercial water modeling tools it works alongside. What you get, what you give up, and what each one costs."
  />

  <ProseSection title="A fair look at the tools you already use" align="center">
    <p>
      InfoWater Pro, WaterCAD, WaterGEMS, and InfoWorks WS Pro are capable
      products with decades of development behind them. Utilities and
      consultants pay for them because they do real work. These comparisons
      don't pretend otherwise.
    </p>
    <p>
      They lay out the trade instead. epanet-js gives you the EPANET 2.3
      engine, an interface built for fast day-to-day modeling, models that stay
      on your machine, published prices with a free tier, and open source code.
      The incumbents give you advanced analysis suites, enterprise
      integrations, and large support organizations, at five-figure annual
      subscriptions on Windows desktops.
    </p>
    <p>
      And because models move in and out of epanet-js as standard EPANET .inp
      files, this is never a switch-or-nothing decision. Plenty of teams do
      their everyday work in epanet-js and keep a commercial seat for the
      specialized analysis that needs one.
    </p>
  </ProseSection>

  <CardGrid
    heading="Pick a comparison"
    subheading="Each page covers features, pricing, and how the two tools work together."
    items={comparePages}
    columns={3}
  />

  <ProseSection title="How these comparisons are made">
    <p>
      Every claim about a competitor comes from public vendor documentation:
      product pages, official help articles, published system requirements, and
      store listings. Competitor prices are quoted only as the vendor publishes
      them, with the date noted on each page. Our own prices come from the
      <a
        href="/pricing"
        class="font-medium text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-800 transition-colors"
        >pricing page</a
      >. If you spot something out of date, tell us and we'll correct it.
    </p>
  </ProseSection>

  <CtaSection
    heading="See it next to your current tool"
    subheading="Open your own model in epanet-js and judge the difference on your network, not ours."
  />
</Layout>
